(6291, '151', 'S.1.2', 'yes', 'Liberata supports the principle of equality of opportunities in employment and opposes all forms of unlawful or unfair discrimination. This includes protection to people with ''protected characteristics''. The list of nine protected characteristics on the grounds of:\r\n\r\n‚Ä¢	age \r\n‚Ä¢	disability \r\n‚Ä¢	gender reassignment \r\n‚Ä¢	marriage and civil partnership \r\n‚Ä¢	pregnancy and maternity \r\n‚Ä¢	race \r\n‚Ä¢	religion or belief \r\n‚Ä¢	sex \r\n‚Ä¢	sexual orientation\r\n\r\nIn addition, we also include:\r\n\r\n‚Ä¢	Trade union activity\r\n\r\nWe believe that it is in the best interests of Liberata and those who work within it to ensure that the talents and skills available from the whole community are considered when employment opportunities arise. To this end, within the framework of the law, we are committed wherever practicable to achieving and maintaining a work force that broadly reflects the local community in which we operate. Liberata will endeavour to ensure that there are no provisions, criteria or practices that put protected persons at a particular disadvantage.\r\n\r\nEvery possible step will be taken to ensure that all employees, whether full time, part time, temporary or contracted, are treated equally and fairly and that decisions on recruitment, selection, training, promotion, career development or employment benefits are based solely on objective and job related criteria. \r\n \r\nLiberata believes that:\r\n‚Ä¢	Equality of opportunity in the workplace is good practice and makes sound business sense\r\n‚Ä¢	Every employee is entitled to a working environment that promotes dignity and respect to all. No form of intimidation, bullying or harassment will be tolerated\r\n‚Ä¢	Breaches of our equal opportunities policy will be regarded as misconduct and could lead to disciplinary proceedings\r\n\r\nThis policy and procedure is supported by Liberata‚Äôs leaders, has been agreed with trade unions and employee representatives and will be monitored and reviewed regularly.\r\n', '8.00'),
(6301, '151', 'S.1.3', 'yes', 'Liberata makes every effort to recruit individuals on the basis of their suitability for the position. Examples of things Liberata does to achieve this include:\r\n‚Ä¢	Producing a role description and person specification for each job. These are reviewed by human resources professionals to ensure that ''protected characteristics'' are not placed at a disadvantage by requirements that are not justifiable\r\n‚Ä¢	Selection for interview is on the basis of meeting the requirements for the position, with no discrimination on any grounds. The grounds for non-selection of applicants will be identified to ensure that discrimination has not taken place\r\n‚Ä¢	Wherever practical, interviews will be conducted by employees who are trained in recruitment and selection procedures and are committed to ensuring that discrimination does not occur\r\n‚Ä¢	All vacancies will be advertised internally throughout Liberata. Exceptions to this will be allowed in certain situations e.g. where an employee suitable for the position is under notice of redundancy, where the position has been identified as a development role for an employee or where it is clear that the vacancy cannot be filled internally due to the technical or senior nature of the position\r\n‚Ä¢	Where used, external adverts will ensure that all members of the community have access to the medium and this may include the use of ethnic magazines, newspapers and job centres as appropriate\r\n‚Ä¢	Care will be taken to ensure that advertisements do not contain any requirements that unlawfully discriminate against any particular groups of people\r\n‚Ä¢	External agencies (including PSL''s) will be expected to operate an equality & diversity policy and procedure which is approved by Liberata\r\n‚Ä¢	All applications will be recorded in terms of the nationality, disability and sex of all applicants for the purposes of monitoring only\r\n‚Ä¢	Recruitment activity will be regularly reviewed to monitor the effectiveness of this policy and action will be taken to correct any bias found\r\n‚Ä¢	When considering other selection methods e.g. psychometric, ability or skills tests, care will be taken to ensure that these do not discriminate due to cultural bias or by requiring, for example, an unjustifiable level of English\r\n‚Ä¢	In certain instances, particular groups may be targeted for recruitment. These will be in line with legislation\r\n\r\nSuccession planning as well as the practices outlined in the recruitment policy will be utilised, as well as ensuring that promotion or transfer opportunities are made available to all employees and appointments are based on capability. All employees have the opportunity to discuss their career aspirations in the course of the performance appraisal process.\r\n\r\nLiberata will endeavour to provide every employee, without any bias, benefits from the provision of training and development activities through:\r\n‚Ä¢	Organising training, wherever possible, to take account of the requirements of different groups of employees, so that groups are not prevented from participating. Where practicable, training events will be held locally and within the normal working day\r\n‚Ä¢	Full training and development opportunities will be made available to all employees to help them achieve and maintain a high standard of performance, irrespective of age, and including part time employees or those working in job share arrangements\r\n‚Ä¢	Equal & Diversity training will be made available to leaders and key employees to ensure that all employees are made aware of the equality & diversity policy and procedure\r\n‚Ä¢	The performance appraisal process is the prime source of assessing training needs for existing employees. For new employees, performance reviews will occur within 3 months of employment and this will produce a training needs assessment (refer to performance appraisal policy and procedure)\r\n‚Ä¢	Leaders and employees will receive training or guidance on how to get the most from the performance appraisal process\r\n\r\nLiberata undertakes to provide the required and desirable level of service to all clients, customers and members of the general public in a manner that is non-discriminatory. Any complaints of discrimination towards anyone that we provide a service to will be treated very seriously and will be thoroughly investigated, which may result in disciplinary proceedings.\r\n\r\nSpecific procedures are developed in relation to the variety of services provided by Liberata, and these aim to ensure that discrimination does not occur in the provision of those services.\r\n\r\nWhere a client, customer or member of the general public acts in a manner that is discriminatory, Liberata will offer support and, where possible, take action to reduce or eliminate the problem.\r\n', '5.00'),
